As a closing comment, may I say that the Committee has worked hard and has done its best to present an intelligent report. The Committee invites fair criticism; but I ask the delegates to be reasonable and not expect ready answers to ques- tions which even a minister of ﬁsheries might not be able to answer. I am not that minister.

In view of the voluminous nature of this report, I suggest it be divided for reading and debating purposes into 12 sections which I shall define as we proceed. The ﬁrst section for treat— ment in this manner is on pages 1~15 of the report which will automatically include Appendix A, the report of the sub-committee on cold storage. Mr. Smallwood You gave the amount paid to fishermen and to labour employed in and around the plantfor 1943-1946, and the ﬁgures rise every year, so that last year that plant paid $234,000 to the ﬁshermen and to the plant workers $69,000. I am trying to get the position generally for the fresh fish industry in 1947. Could you give us an

outline of what it might be? Mr. Job It is impossible to give any outline; we do not know what the position is going to be. We have not made any contracts. The American market at the present time is in a bad condition. The British market has not purchased any fish. It is utterly impossible to make any commitments. I would not risk stating what I think would hap- pen. We are all hoping that if we get a contract in the United States and if the American market recovers, we will produce on the same scale.
